{{Infobox music genre <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Music genres -->
| name              = Comedy hip hop
| bgcolor           = darkblue
| color             = white
| stylistic_origins ={{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Comedy music]]}}
| instruments       = {{hlist|[[Beatboxing]]|[[Singing|Vocals]]}}
| derivatives       = [[Satirical hip hop]]
| fusiongenres      = 
}}

'''Comedy hip hop''' or '''comedy rap''', is a subgenre of [[hip hop music]] that is comedic in nature, often incorporating satirical lyrics. While many examples of comedy hip hop could be considered a [[parody]] of the hip hop genre, in the case of artists who merely incorporate humor into their more serious, [[wikt:purist|purist]] hip hop styles, such as [[Eminem]] and [[Ludacris]], this is not necessarily the case.

[[Run DMC]]'s "[[Christmas in Hollis]]" from 1987 is comedy rap, and [[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince]] were solidly in the comedy rap genre with the 1988 song "[[Parents Just Don't Understand]]." [[N.W.A]] and [[Ice Cube]]'s early albums were not as comedic and lighthearted as The Fresh Prince but did incorporate humor.

Before the darker themes that are characteristic of the [[Gangsta rap]] of the 1990s, comedy hip hop, with its lighter and more humorous style, came to prominence in the 1980s,<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|last=allmusic|title=about comedy rap|url=http://www.allmusic.com/style/comedy-rap-ma0000012206|accessdate=30 December 2012}}</ref> carried by popular acts such as the [[Beastie Boys]]. Various influential comedy hip hop groups began in the late 1980s, such as [[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince]], [[Kid 'n Play]], [[Das EFX]] and [[Fu-Schnickens]] and throughout the late 1990s and 2000s, rappers including [[Eminem]], [[Ludacris]] and [[Afroman]] gained popularity, as did rappers such as [[Hopsin]]. [[Rucka Rucka Ali]] is an artist who experiments with comedy hip hop filled with racism, such as his song, "What The Black Says". [["Weird Al" Yankovic]] has made entries to this music genre, along with [[Nerdcore]]. "[[Thrift Shop]]" by [[Macklemore & Ryan Lewis]] is also a well-known song of comedy hip hop. While few rappers make comedy hip hop their focus with the exception of a few, mainly [[Lil Dicky]] and [[Ugly God]], the genre maintains a substantial loyal following.

Outside the English-speaking world, the genre spread in the 1990s, with bands and artists such as the German group [[Fettes Brot]], the [[Sweden Finns|Swedish-Finnish]] artist [[Markoolio]] and the French group Svinkels.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://musicamscire.blogspot.fr/2011/10/le-comedy-rap.html |title=Le Comedy Rap |last1=Cardenas |first1=Fabricio |date=13 October 2011 |website=Musicam scire |language=fr |access-date=3 June 2016 |quote=}}</ref>

